     <profileDesc>
        <abstract><p><persName ref="#gokulDas">Gokul Das</persName>, the chief of <placeName ref="#devgarh">Devgarh</placeName> and a noble in the <placeName ref="#udaipur">Udaipur</placeName> court, issues an order to the landlords of <placeName ref="#devgarh">Devgarh</placeName> promising that he will not remove their perquisites without cause,
           nor punish them without an inquiry by the brotherhood of landlords. This order and the dispute it responds to informed <persName ref="#jamesTod">James Tod's</persName> understanding of Rajput political systems.<note>Tod published a translation of this document and the petition it addresses. See <ref type="bibl" target="#tod1829v1">Tod, Annals and Antiquities, vol. 1, p. 199-200</ref>.</note>
        It is the upper of the two documents copied on one folio in the manuscript.</p></abstract>       
